<i>
Parameter Estimation
</i>
</td>
<td valign=3D"TOP" width=3D"85%">
<!-- Add main text below -->
For the full sample case, the maximum likelihood estimator of the
scale parameter is the sample mean.
<a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/apr/section4/apr412.htm=
#LikelihoodFunctionExamplesforReliabilityData">
Maximum likelihood estimation for the exponential distribution</a>
is discussed in the chapter on reliability (Chapter 8).  It is also
discussed in chapter 19 of
<a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/eda/section4/eda43.htm#=
Johnson">Johnson, Kotz, and
Balakrishnan</a>.

</td>
</tr>
<!-- end paragraph -->

<!-- begin paragraph -->
<tr>
<td width=3D"15%" valign=3D"top">
<!-- Add marginal notes below -->
<i>
Comments
</i>
</td>
<td valign=3D"TOP" width=3D"85%">
<!-- Add main text below -->
The exponential distribution is primarily used in
<a href=3D"https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/apr/apr.htm">reliabilit=
y</a> applications.
The exponential distribution is used to model data with a
constant failure rate (indicated by the hazard plot which is
simply equal to a constant).

</td>
</tr>
<!-- end paragraph -->

